Set Up the PostgreSQL Database
Create a new database for the application by running this SQL command in your database client (like psql).
          CREATE DATABASE benefits_db;
Install Dependencies
Open your computer's terminal or command prompt and navigate to your project folder.
          cd path/to/your/employee-benefits
Initialize a Node.js project. This creates a package.json file.
          npm init -y
Install the necessary packages (Express for the server, pg for PostgreSQL, and CORS for cross-origin requests).
          npm install express pg cors

After installation, your project directory will look like this:
          employee-benefits/
          â”œâ”€â”€ ðŸ“‚ node_modules/      <-- Created by npm
          â”œâ”€â”€ ðŸ“‚ public/
          â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ ðŸ“œ index.html
          â”‚   â””â”€â”€ ðŸ“œ hr.html
          â”œâ”€â”€ ðŸ“œ package.json      <-- Created by npm
          â”œâ”€â”€ ðŸ“œ package-lock.json  <-- Created by npm
          â””â”€â”€ ðŸ“œ server.js


 Run the Application
 Start the backend server by running this command from your terminal.
          node server.js

  You can now open public/index.html and public/hr.html in your browser using the "Open with Live Server" option in VS Code to use the application.
